For me personally, the number one metric is based on my happiness. And happiness here does not necessarily always mean pleasure or joy as I am doing it... I would imagine my future self reflecting on the decision that I am about to make, and see if I would be proud of feel a sense of contentment that I made the decision to do whatever I am about to do.

P.S. If you want to see the full interview, then go to @startcanadapodcast 👈 for the link.

node.text:
Do you you agree?👀 Your social media's feed says more about you then what's currently happening in the world. Part of the reason why you keep seeing negative news on your feed is because you keep interacting with those type of content. And the algorithm takes note of your behavior to keep feeding you content that you are likely to interact with...

Anyway, this is a snippet of an hour long interview I did with @startcanadapodcast 2 weeks ago where we talked about social media marketing for entrepreneurs.

Go check out their page @startcanadapodcast 👈to see the full episode if you want some free tips on growing your business utilizing social media as a tool. 📲

node.title: @iamdaviddang - Social media is just exposing us🙈

May be an image of text that says 'Scott Lynn @scottlynn At the age of 15 starte Virtumundo (later renamed Treeloot) with a little skill ano a ot of luck It quickly became one of the most popular games on the Internet in the late 90's. (A thread)'.

node.text:
Where do billionaire entrepreneurs come from? Sometimes it’s an attic in Kansas City. That’s where Scott Lynn started his first business Virtumundo (later renamed Treeloot) when he was 15 years old. It quickly became the most popular game and one of the largest advertisers on the Internet in the late 90s.

Later, Scott founded Adknowledge, which became the fourth largest digital advertising marketplace behind Google, Yahoo and MSN. A lifelong entrepreneur, he continued to found a series of technology companies which have been valued at over $1 billion.

Throughout all these pursuits and changes in his life, there was one thing he kept constant: his passion for art. Inspired by his mother, who was an art teacher, he became one of the top art collectors in the world. His passion has made good business sense: contemporary art prices outpaced the S&P 500 total return almost two-fold over the same period, according to data compiled from public sources.

Contemporary art is an asset, so why can’t the typical investor access it? Real estate, gold, and other alternatives have been securitized, so why not art?

Now, Scott spends his days on the top floor of his New York office for his new company, Masterworks, that lets you invest through fractional ownership. The platform already has over 180,000 registered users of all types from around the globe.

His sole first exit returned 32% net to investors, and he’s just getting started. What’s your twenty-year story? Comment below and check the link in our bio to learn more about Masterworks and skip their waitlist.
-
@masterworks.io

May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Stephen Campolo @stephencampolo #1 Follow the 80/20 Rule Focus on eating healthy, whole foods 80% of the time, and allow for the foods you love 20% of the time. Try to stay away from processed food. 80% of how you look is determined by what you eat.'.

Photo by Business| Mindset| Motivation🔥 on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Stephen Campolo @stephencampolo #2- Exercise for 30- 60 minutes per day. Try to do it first thing in the morning before the day gets busy. Your productivity and energy will skyrocket.'.
